          "body": "The chapter is framed by two divine actions: *the LORD hurled* a great wind on the sea (1:4) and *the LORD appointed* a great fish (1:17). Between them everything else happens — but nothing else *initiates*. The storm is not chance; the fish is not coincidence. Even the lot that falls on Jonah (1:7) operates under Proverbs 16:33's commentary — *its every decision is from the LORD*. The chapter's deepest theology is that the same God who issued the commission in 1:2 issues every providential pressure that brings the disobedient prophet back. The pursuit is the love. The storm is a mercy. The fish is salvation. Hebrews 12:6 — whom the LORD loves He disciplines — is the New Testament gloss on Jonah 1."
